description:
Straits is a Chess-like game for two, played on a 9 x 11 hourglass-shaped grid of checkered squares.  Each player has nineteen pieces of his own color: one Flag-ship, 7 Turret-ships, 8 Torpedo boats, and 3 Gun-boats.  Their rules of movement are as follows:

)Flag-ship - it moves and captures like a Queen in Chess, but it cannot be captured and must not move into check or remain in check.
)Turret-ship - it moves and captures like a Rook in Chess.
)Torpedo boat - it moves and captures like a Bishop in Chess, and is consequently bound to squares of the same color.
)Gun-boat - it moves one square in any direction, but can capture only diagonally.

The first player to move his Flag-ship to the board's central square or who checkmates the Flag-ship of his opponent wins the game.

Splatball - Suburban Legends is a board game conversion of Oversoul Games&rsquo; popular &ldquo;Flat Out War&rdquo;
expansion, &ldquo;Splatball.&rdquo;
You still have the kidz battling for control of the neighbourhood with their splat markers, but there are plenty
of other changes than just the addition of a board.

The game can be downloaded for free from ...

http://www.oversoul-games.com/oversoul_download.html

from the rules:
"Bobby Butterfingers pulls at his wizard&rsquo;s coat. This time he must not spoil his magician&rsquo;s exam. Slowly and carefully, he takes the big magic cube from the pedestal. 'Now, how did that correct spell go?'. Then he remembers. With a firm voice he shouts 'Butterfingers Cube', takes his magic ring and lets it skillfully fall into the cube. The other apprentices hold their breath - if nothing falls out of the cube, Bobby will pass the test.

Whoever can hold the magic cube with a steady hand and skillfully let the objects fall inside, will be left at the end of the game with the fewest objects in front of them."

Welcome to the Roman Republic! The aim of the game is to win political control of the Republic. The two areas of play are the Provinces in the electoral circuit and the Offices. Players will place influence tokens in the Provinces in the hope of winning provincial elections which provide influence. Magistrates and Governors also provide influence, and can be used to take special actions which will help players defeat their rivals. The game ends once all 24 Provinces have been decided, in which case the player with the most influence from both the Provinces and the Offices wins.

Equipment Needed:
a) 1 standard piecepack;
b) about $2 in change to represent gold (ideal breakdown would be 50 x 1c, 10 x 5c, 10 x 10c;
c) cubes in 4 different colors to use as influence markers (20 per player);
d) a printout of the Table of Offices from the rules

Rules can be found on the Piecepack Wiki.

Game System

    Piecepack Game System

&ldquo;Luke, Han and Leia need to get back to the Millennium Falcon in the Death Star&rsquo;s Docking  Bay. But Vader and his minions are in hot pursuit.&rdquo;

The game is played on the map from the Escape From the Death Star miniature game, or the players may design a custom map. The object of the game is to destroy all of your opponent&rsquo;s characters. Each player controls three characters. The Rebel player plays Luke Skywalker, Princess Leia, and Han Solo. The Empire player plays Darth Vader, an anonymous Stormtrooper, and (from the Episode III cutting room floor?) Boba Fett.
Each character has a deck of cards containing a specific number of Power, Toughness, and Force cards in allocations intended to represent the relative abilities of the characters. These cards are used to resolve combat. Movement of the characters is determined by drawing Area cards.

&ldquo;Players are modern-day, rich, athletic, leisure-minded adventurers.&rdquo;

The players choose one of three traits for their adventurer: &ldquo;World Class Athlete&rdquo;, &ldquo;Filthy Rich&rdquo;, or &ldquo;No Responsibilities.&rdquo; The players collect and play resource cards allowing them to complete adventures such as &ldquo;Running of the Bulls&rdquo;, &ldquo;Sahara Marathon&rdquo;, &ldquo;Ski the South Pole&rdquo;, and &ldquo;Suborbital Space Flight.&rdquo;

The game ends when there are no Adventure cards left, at which point the player with the highest Victory Point total wins.

&ldquo;A two-player card game of modern tank combat. Each player starts the game with 16 AFV (Armored Fighting Vehicle) Tokens. Reduce your opponent to 0 AFV tokens.&rdquo;

Each player starts with a hand of ten cards drawn from a common deck. The card types include Offensive Attack, Defensive Attack, Units, Weapons, Movement, Obstacle, Protection, Leadership, Morale, and Reconnaissance. Each turn has 8 phases: Deploy Phase, Leadership Phase, Reconnaissance Phase, Defensive Phase, Defensive Movement Phase, Offensive Phase, Offensive Movement Phase, and Redeploy Phase.

In order to win the game, a player must play cards to mount successful attacks which result in the opponent's loss of AFV tokens.

&ldquo;A card game for 2 to 4 players, or more. Each player controls a country during the First Industrial Revolution. Players try to develop their economies as quickly as possible.&rdquo; The game is played with two sets of cards, an Industry Deck and an Event Deck.

There are seven categories of &ldquo;Resources&rdquo; that are tracked for each country: Food, Population (Skilled and Unskilled Labor), Fossil Fuels, Steel (Production Capacity), Transportation, Guns, and Luxury Goods (Peacetime Consumption). Each country begins with an equal amount of resources.

&ldquo;The first player to have a combined score of 100+ in Guns and Luxury Goods wins. If more than 1 person gets 100+ on the same turn, the Player with the higher score wins. If it is still tied, use Transportation, and then Population, as tie-breakers.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Solo Card Game System simulating the Arab Israeli Wars 1948+. Currently only cards set for the Israeli War of Independence is available.  The player takes the role of the Israelis. Arab deployments are automatic.&rdquo;

The game is played on three Fronts: the Northern Frontier (Galilee), Central Frontier (Jerusalem), and Southern front (Negev). Each Front is represented by six Territory Tokens, all of which are under the control of the Israelis (the solo player) at the start of the game. If the Arabs are able to acquire control all six tokens on any one Front, you suffer a Complete Loss. If you win all battles on all three Fronts for two turns in a row, you achieve a Decisive Victory. If the Arabs run out of unit cards, you achieve an Attrition Victory.

The Unit cards are intended to represent Arab and Israeli forces involved in the 1948 hostilities. Units are drawn and played to the Fronts - Arab units to designated Fronts and Israeli cards as desired by the player. Each turn one card is drawn from the Event deck. The Event card confers benefits to one side or the other.

&ldquo;Original Victorian Themed version of the WarpQuest Gaming System. Each player controls a party of adventuring archaeologists and treasure hunters trying to be the first to get some, relic, artifact, or treasure and bring it back.&rdquo;

The game is played on a single winding path of connected squares, generally 30 spaces long. The action is driven by cards drawn from the scenario specific deck. The mapboard path and card deck are subdivided to represent different stages of the adventure. Typically one deck is used for the first fifteen spaces on the path -- the second deck is used for the last fifteen spaces on the path.

The scenarios available for Artifact include: Depths of the Earth (first travel through the Earth&rsquo;s crust, then adventure in the Lost World of dinosaurs), Mummys Tomb (first travel down the Nile, then explore the tomb searching for the treasure of the pharaoh), Lost Continent of Atlantis (travel deep below the sea by submarine, then explore the lost continent in diving suits searching for the Pearl Trident), and The Shadow of a Dark God (a Cthulhu style scenario where the players first investigate a friend&rsquo;s death, then search a cult temple).

A tabletop &ldquo;Space Opera Miniature Game&rdquo; based on the designer&rsquo;s story of the same name.

&ldquo;It is now the dawn of the five hundredth millennium since the birth of Christ. The Empire of Man has reached out into the intergalactic depths of space, and a lost son has been found&hellip;unfortunately. The great Quantumliners of the Scouting Guild has encountered an artificial species completely inimical to humanity. Each alien robot is directly controlled by a single artificial intelligence known as Ladek! The twisted, disembodied mind of the former human scientist now lords over these automaton artifacts of a long extinct race. They have invaded every galaxy controlled by man&rsquo;s glorious Imperium, and have begun a systematic extermination of every human life it encounters. While the Imperial Navy and Marine Corp defends the home galaxies against the attacks of these monsters, it falls to the Scouting Guild to hunt out and destroy Ladek units along the Imperium&rsquo;s frontier worlds.&rdquo;

&ldquo;One player plays the Human Imperial Scouts and the other plays the Ladek Marine Robots. Forces are &lsquo;purchased&rsquo; by means of points. Both sides must decide how many points they should begin with. I highly suggest beginning a campaign (a series of wargames between the same player(s)) with fifty points for each side.&rdquo; The object of the game is to destroy all the opposing units.

&ldquo;Card game. Simulates the Battle of Britain. July-September 1940. Players will have to make their own sets of cards.
The RAF and Luftwaffe have their own unique decks. Both decks have 62 cards. Notice that most cards have a force value. The Germans also need 20 tokens to represent bomb damage.&rdquo;

Both players start the game with four cards. The players draw two cards at the start of each turn, with the maximum hand size at the end of the turn being eight cards. The German player has the option not to play a raid, in which case the turn ends. If the German player plays a raid, the players alternate playing force cards until neither player wants to play a card. The strength of the opposing forces are compared. If the RAF has a higher force total, the raid is stopped. If the German has the higher force total, then the amount of bombing damage caused by the raid is determined and added to the German&rsquo;s score.

&ldquo;If the German&rsquo;s accumulate 20 points of bombing damage then they win. Hitler decides to go ahead with operation Sealion. If the German player goes to draw a card and there are no cards left in his deck the British win. Hitler postpones operation Sealion indefinitely.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. Highly abstracted skirmish level combat. Simulation of a counter-terrorist team operation. One side is the commandos: Delta/SAS/GSG-9/GIGN/etc. The other side is Terrorists holding hostages in a building. Victory: To win the Delta team must kill all the terrorists before taking 4 casualties. The Terrorists win if they kill 4 Delta team members, which allows them time to kill the hostages.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the commandos and terrorists. The terrorist group is composed of one Leader and seven Followers. The commando force consists of one Team Leader, three Shooters, two Demolitions Experts, and two Snipers. A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw hands of cards from the common deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

&ldquo;The Special Forces have many more cards at their disposal, which reflects their high degree of training & experience.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Card game for 2 players. Based on the comic book character Doctor Strange. One player is the forces of good. The other player is the forces of evil. Victory: If, for 2 turns in a row, starting on turn 10, a player has no viable Characters in play, his opponent wins.&rdquo;

A viable character is one of the player&rsquo;s character cards that is not Killed, Incapacitated, Exiled, or Captured. Each viable character may make one attack each turn, resolved by die roll and card play. A successful attack can result in the attacker gaining control over one of the opposing player&rsquo;s character. Characters may also be captured and rescued.

"The Deck: Players share a common deck. Card Types include: Characters, Companions, Locations, Items, Modifiers, Powers, Attacks, Events."

&ldquo;Simulation of a Pistol Duel circa 1700+. Duelists agree to one of the following: One Shot, Multiple Shots (2,3,or 4), First Blood, Death. They may also forgo the Speed element of the Duel and allow the Challenged to fire first.&rdquo;

The custom deck is divided into four suits: Speed, Aim, Range, and Hit. The Speed cards determine who fires first. Your Aim cards must total higher than your opponent&rsquo;s Range cards to score a hit. The total of your Hit cards, when compared to those of your opponent, determine whether a player who was hit is wounded or killed.

Your success in the duel falls into one of four categories: &ldquo;You are Killed: Major Defeat. You are Wounded: Minor Defeat. Opponent Wounded: Minor Victory. Opponent Killed: Major Victory.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Solo card game. WWII Western Front. Player controls a squad of American GI&rsquo;s on patrol. Fight German units.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The Decks: There are 2 separate decks: The GI Deck and the Patrol Deck. They have separate discard piles.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The Squad: Your squad has 15 soldiers. Use tokens to keep track of soldiers.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Victory: Get completely through the Patrol Deck. You lose if all of your squad members become casualties.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Solo card, dice & board game. Based on the Movie of the same name. Take on the role of Snake Plisskin.&rdquo;

The game consists of seventeen scenes based on events and characters from the film. To aid in advancing through the scenes, a gameboard with a track of seventeen spaces can be drawn. The player gains cards at various stages. There are four different card types. Each type of card gives a bonus to a different type of die roll.

&ldquo;Victory: Escape & Activate the Electro-Magnetic Pulse in the last Step. Losing: You lose if you ever get killed, or you do not get the antidote in 10 hours.&rdquo;

Descriptions from the rules:

&ldquo;Solo Dice Game. Simulation of an American solo F-14 Bombing Mission in the Middle East circa 1987. Pretty much like Microprose F-15 II. No realism, I think no Tomcat would do a solo bombing mission.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Mission: The mission consists 25 waypoints, first and last of which is home base. Draw the waypoints as circles connected with lines on a piece of paper. There are two targets in a mission, primary and secondary targets. First target is 2d6 waypoints from the 1st waypoint, the second 2d6 waypoints from the first target. Roll on the target table to determine what the targets are.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Scoring: Keep a running tally of points and kills while you play. You get awarded medals and promotions accordingly. You start with no medals and at a rank of 2nd Lt.&rdquo;

Rules for a two-player cooperative variant are included.

&ldquo;Miniatures rules for aerial skirmishes. All combatants (Fliers) include a mount with usually one rider.&rdquo;

The game features a diverse assortment of aerial combatants, all rated in two classes: Speed and Maneuverability. The Speed rating determines maximum speed, acceleration and deceleration rates, climb and dive rates, and modifiers for dodging and initiative. The Maneuverability rating determines turning rate, dodging ability, and initiative bonus. A wide variety of attack types are provided for: Spell, Poison, Ram, Grab, Petrification/Paralyze, Stun, Web/Net, Mesmerize, Fear, Smoke/Gas, and Fire/Acid Attacks.

With over fifty Mounts described in the game, Fantasy Fliers allows for just about every type of aerial combat you could think of &ndash; from bees, wasps, and butterflies to magic carpets, flying skulls, biplanes, and Pegasus.

&ldquo;Card game for 2 players. WWI Aerial Dogfight Simulation. One player is the Germans, the other is the Allies. Victory: The first player to shoot down 4 enemy machines wins the battle. Use coins to keep track of &lsquo;Kills.&rsquo;&rdquo;

The game is played using a custom card deck comprised of six suits made up of twelve cards numbered 1 to 12. These suits are Pilots, Allied Planes, German Planes, Tactics, Shooting, and Flying. All of the cards are usable by either player except for the Plane Cards - Allied Planes may only be used by the Allied player and German Planes may only be used by the German player.

Each turn the players are dealt hands of five cards. They may discard and redraw up to three cards. Each player then plays an Attack which must include a Pilot card and a Plane card. An attack may also include one card from each of the other three suits (Shooting, Tactics, and Flying.) A kill is scored when the total value of the cards played in an Attack is equal to or greater than the Attack played by the opposing player.

&ldquo;Card Game based on the RPG Gamma World by TSR. You are a leader of a Gamma World Enclave. Recruit and equip your followers. Send your followers to capture ruins that will aid your cause. Victory: The game ends when all cards have been drawn from the deck. The player controlling the most location cards wins.&rdquo;

The game uses a custom card deck composed of the following types of cards: Weapons, Armor, Vehicles, Steeds, Equipment, Events, Mutations, Foes, and Locations.

Each turn a player receives a base allocation of two Action Points. Some cards will provide additional Action Points. Action Points are spent to perform the following actions: recruit one Follower, draw one card from the deck, play an Item card, or attack a Location.

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. Battle between Jedi knights & Federation allies on Genosis. Takes place in the Star Wars Universe (Episode II). Each figure represents a Hero, Jedi, Creature or Unit of Troops. Victory: The game ends after you go through the deck twice when Yoda and the clone trooper gunships arrive. The player who has killed the most opposing units wins.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combat units. There are ten Jedi units, twenty-two Federation units, and three Creature units.

A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend. The Creatures in the arena are not allied with the Jedi or Federation. Either player may cause Creatures to Move or Attack by playing Creature Cards.

&ldquo;G.I. Joe vs Cobra. 2 player game: Board, Cards, Dice. There are 2 decks. One player gets the Joe Deck. The other player gets the Cobra Deck. Victory: You win if you ever capture your opponent&rsquo;s base, or you control all &lsquo;Urban&rsquo; spaces on the board.&rdquo;

The game is played on an 8x8 grid with spaces large enough to hold a card. The G.I. Joe base is in one corner of the board and the Cobra base is in the opposite corner. The remaining 62 spaces are a random mix of eight terrain types: Jungle, Swamp, Sea, Desert, Mountain, Forest, Urban, and Arctic.

Each player starts with four Teams and a hand of cards. Each card has the name and statistics for a soldier. The cards are placed under each Team counter to represent the soldiers in that Team.

Teams engage in combat by moving into the same space as an opposing Team. Combat is resolved based on one of three unit factors (as determined randomly by a die roll): Firepower, Close Combat, or Tactics. Combat bonuses are given for various factors, including having a team with soldiers from the same service branch or when units are defending their base. Combat resolution also takes into consideration artillery units, armor units vs. anti-armor, and air units vs. &ldquo;anti-air.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Sci-Fi themed board & card game for 2 players. Each figure represents a vehicle, mech, or infantry squad. Victory: You rout the enemy if you destroy 9+ of his units.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combat units. Each side starts with sixteen units: two Mechs, six Vehicles, and eight Infantry.

A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend. In addition, Obstacle cards may be played in response to movement cards, sometimes casuing the moving unit to sustain damage. Other special cards allow a unit to both move and attack in the same turn.

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. Napoleonic warfare theme. Abstract skirmish level combat. Each figure represents a company or unit of men. Victory: You rout the enemy if you destroy 9+ of his units.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chess board or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combat units. Each side starts with sixteen units: eight Infantry, four Cavalry, and four Artillery. A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

Optional rules provide for terrain, which comes in six types: Clear, Deep Water, Forest, Hill, Redoubt, and Marsh. The terrain features impact movement and combat in various ways.

&ldquo;Board Game for 2 players. One player takes the role of the Hero Beowulf. The other player takes the role of the Monster Grendel. Victory: Slay your Foe. The first player to reduce his opponent to zero or less hits wins. Each player starts the game with 20 Hit Points.&rdquo;

The game board is a track 13 spaces long. Each space on the board is a named location. These range from the Great Hall and other places favorable to the Danes at one end, to the dangerous swamps at the opposite end which favor Grendel.

Attack, Defense, and Ally Cards are used in combat. The other cards are used to perform various functions, such as assisting in travel or healing wounds. Some cards may be used to impede your opponent&rsquo;s travel or to require your opponent to discard cards.

&ldquo;Combat rules for plastic Army men."

"Armies start at opposite ends of the room. Turn Sequence: Each figure gets to move once and attack once per turn. Mortars, machine guns & artillery can either move or attack during a turn.&rdquo;

Several different combat resolution mechanisms are included in the rules. The mechanism to be used depends on the nature of the attacking unit. For instance, a submachinegun attack is resolved as follows: &ldquo;Standing 15 feet away from the target throw 3 marbles simultaneously.&rdquo; On the other hand, for a flamethrower: &ldquo;Stand over the attacker. Drop a tennis ball from the tip of your nose.&rdquo;

In addition, a six-sided die is rolled to determine what means is used to resolve hand-to-hand attacks between infantry units within two inches of each other. The die roll may call for these conflicts to be resolved by means such as arm wrestling, a staring contest, or rock-paper-scissors.

The &ldquo;Safety Rules&rdquo; note that players should wear goggles at all times.

&ldquo;Card game for 2-4 players. Ancient Greek Olympics Theme. Players try to win the most Events. Victory: The player with the most Victory Points at the end of the game wins.&rdquo;

The game is played using two decks. The Ability Deck contains sixty cards. The Event Deck specifies the twelve events in which the players will compete, which include Discus, Javelin, Horse Racing, and Boxing.

The Ability cards played by the players determine who will be awarded the Gold, Silver, and Bronze medals in each event.

&ldquo;Wargame for 2 or more players. Mythological Greek theme. Victory: Occupy all 6 City States on the Board.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Tiles are used to make the Map. Chits are used to represent Units. Cards are used for Events. Counters are stacked with units to record damage. Tile, chit, counter, and card sets are common to all players. Six sided dice are needed to play.&rdquo;

The map is generated by randomly distributing the Terrain Tiles on a chess board or 8x8 grid. The Tiles come in two water varieties (Sea, Abyss) and five land varieties (Coastal, City State, Forest, Mountains, Ruins.)

Each player starts the game with one Hero unit located on a City State space. The players must recruit various heroes, men, and monsters to aid them in their conquest of Greece. The players will face random events reflecting the blessings of the Greek Gods or disasters and dangers.

&ldquo;Fantasy Card game. 2-6 players. Players take the role of Arthurian Knights on the quest for the Holy Grail. Object: The first player to accumulate 7 'Quest' tokens is the winner.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Materials: There are 65 cards in the deck. Players will have to create their own cards in order to play. A six sided die is required to play. 7 'quest tokens' per player are needed.&rdquo;

Each player&rsquo;s turn consists of two to four phases. In the Draw Phase, two cards a drawn. This is followed by the Fate phase, in which the player decides whether or not to quest for the grail. If the player declines to quest, the turn ends.

If a player decides to quest, the Adventure Phase comes next. The opponent to the left of the phasing player may play a Test Card. If the phasing player is able to pass the Test, then the other opponents may continue to play Test Cards against the phasing player. This continues until no opponents offer a Test Card. If any Test is failed, the turn ends. If all Tests are met, then the Quest Phase follows. Quests are resolved based on a die roll combined with Aid cards played by the phasing player.

&ldquo;If you accumulate 7 Quest tokens, than you are deemed worthy to receive the Holy Grail, and you win.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Solitaire Card game. Based on the side-scroller video game of the same name.&rdquo;

The player starts with five characters, a Warrior, Dwarf, Woman Warrior, Sprite, and Centaur. Each character is rated for Hits, Magic, Speed, Damage Bonus, and Weapon.

The card deck contains six types of cards: Attack, Defend, Heal, Speed, Magic, and Foe. The player must defeat a series of Foes to reach and confront the Death Adder. The player wins the game by defeating the Death Adder.

&ldquo;Card game for 2 players. Based on Hindu Mythology. One player is the Good Blue Skinned Rama. The other is the Evil 10-headed, 40-Armed Demon King Ravana. Victory: Kill the opposing Leader.&rdquo;

Each player has a unique deck containing, in addition to one Leader card, eight basic card types: Heroes, Troops, Weapons, Armor, Modifiers, Strikes, Defenses, and Events.

Players can hold a hand of up to eight cards. The players alternate being the attacker, at which time they have the option of choosing to attack with some, all, or no units. The defender chooses which units will block attacking units. All unblocked units attack the opposing leader. Damage markers are used to record combat results.

&ldquo;Teams of Goblins run around, get into mischief, wreak havoc, and try to not get killed. Not unlike Space Scouts.&rdquo;

The game is played using a custom deck containing four types of cards: Mission, Threat, Mishap, and Aid. Each player starts with four Goblin characters, each of which has two to three skills.

The object of the game is to be the first player to accumulate a specific number of Victory Points. Victory Points are gained by completing Missions (the amount awarded depending on the difficulty) and overcoming Threats. Victory Points may be spent to give your Goblin characters new skills and to replace a Goblin character than has been lost.

Based on the PC auto racing game of the same name.

&ldquo;A cardgame for 2 to 6 players. It tries to recreate some of the twists of the original PC game, but incorporates more than that: card management, timing of card play, bluff.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The game is played on four regular rounds and a great Final Lap round. The regular rounds are the main moves of the race, where the players will struggle to better their positions on the race. The Final Lap round will be the outcome of all the tactics and choices made during the race . . . The winner of the race is the player which car has moved furthest on the track.&rdquo;

The rules are in English, Italian, and French.

&ldquo;2 Player Dice and Board Game. Backgammon Variant with specialized pieces. Napoleonic Military Theme.&rdquo;

The game is played on a regular Backgammon board. Each player uses three six-sided dice and has a set of sixteen pieces composed of four Infantry, two each of Skirmishers, Horse Artillery, Field Artillery, Light Cavalry, and Heavy Cavalry, one General and one Lines of Communication. Units are rated for two capabilities &ndash; shoot and move. In addition, each type of unit has one or more Special Abilities.

There are five types of victory: Strategic - capture your opponent&rsquo;s Lines of Communication Unit; Morale - kill or capture your opponent&rsquo;s General and 4+ other Units; Attrition - destroy any 8+ enemy Units; Outflank - have 4+ of your units on your opponent&rsquo;s back six points; and Positional - have 8+ of your units on your opponent&rsquo;s front six points.

&ldquo;2 Armies of Wind-up toys duke it out. Based on an old video game. Victory: Players get 1 point every time a toy goes off their opponent&rsquo;s side of the board. The game ends when the counter pile is empty and there are no toys left on the board (or no toy has been able to move in 5 turns.) The player with the most points wins the game.&rdquo;

The game is played on an 8x8 grid or chess board. Six and eight-sided dice are required. There are twelve wind-up toys in the game, each with its own counter.

At the beginning of the game, all of the toy counters are placed in a cup or face down in a pile. At the start of a player&rsquo;s turn, a toy counter is drawn and placed at that player&rsquo;s end of the board. Each of the player's toys moves once. The type of move each piece can make is determined by a die roll.

&ldquo;Dead Rabbits vs Bowery Boys. Simulation of an all out Street Melee between two rival NY urban gangs circa 1864. Victory: Kill your opponents Leader.&rdquo;

The game is played on a 6x8 grid (it may be convenient to use a portion of a chess board). Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combatants. Each player starts with sixteen units: one Leader, seven Axers, and eight Knifers.

Each turn both players roll five six-sided dice. Each die result corresponds to one of six possible moves listed on the Result chart (such as &ldquo;1 - One knifer may kill an opponent in an orthogonally adjacent space&rdquo; or &ldquo;5 - Move one of your men two spaces in any direction.&rdquo;) The players alternate using one die result to make a move. After both players have used their five dice, the next turn begins and the process is repeated.

&ldquo;PREMISE: This plays like a cross between Chess and Backgammon. SET UP: Regular Chessboard and pieces plus two dice. OBJECT: Move all of your men to your opponents back row.&rdquo;

Each turn a player rolls two dice to determine which pieces may be moved (a chart assigns each number on a d6 to one type of chess piece). Pieces may only be moved forward or sideways, not backward. However, a piece can only capture when it is moving forwards. When a piece is captured it is returned to the back row of the owning player.

A short-game variant provides that the game is won by the first player to move a King off the board.

&ldquo;Trivia game for 1 or more players. Winning: The first player to score 35 points is the winner.&rdquo;

The game consists of a custom deck of cards. Each card describes a category. A card is drawn and the players are given a set amount of time to write a list of items that come within the category. Once the time limit has expired, the players reveal their lists. Each correct answer scores one point, but a player may not score more than ten points in a single turn.

Categories on the cards include: Names of Physicists, Names of Cuts of Beef, Names of Computer Programming Languages, Names of Antibiotics, Names of Bad Guys in Star Wars and The First 10 Elements on the Periodic Table.

&ldquo;Card Game for 2 Players. French Indian War Theme circa 1753-1763.&rdquo;

One player takes on the role of the British forces, the other player is the French. The game is played with a custom deck of cards. The cards include leaders, troops, Indians, and defenses.

The object of the game is to win all of the forts, represented by Fort Tokens. At the start of the game each player has five Fort Tokens. The Tokens are won when the Attacking player is able to play the winning cards in the Expedition and Siege phases of a turn. Solitaire and optional rules are included.

&ldquo;This game is a futuristic race of the WipeOut or Star Wars episode 1 kind.&rdquo;

&ldquo;A single championship is made of one or several circuits. Except if otherwise voted by all players, all circuit will have to be played three time, once for each category. Each race belongs to one special category and has special rules and only the third one allows the use of weapons. Categories are: Total Speed Way - a speed race where the initial risks bidding is essential, Dragster Show - an die-fast competition where wreckage are far from being uncommon, Destruction Derby - where the pilots are allowed weapons aboard.&rdquo;

There are four different kinds of racing ships, each rated for Speed, Hit Points, and &ldquo;Space Available&rdquo; for further customization. Pilots are rated for Piloting and G-Endurance.

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. Space Combat in the Games Workshop Warhammer 40K Space Fleet Universe. Pick your Fleet: Tyranid, Imperial, Eldar, or Necron. Abstract skirmish level combat. Each figure represents a single Ship (unit). Victory: You win if you Destroy the opposing Flagship.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combat units. Each player has a fleet of sixteen ships comprised of one flagship and four other types of ships, which vary depending on the type of fleet chosen. Each ship is rated for hits, movement, and size.

Each type of fleet uses a custom deck of cards which is central to the play of the game. The players draw hands of cards from their decks. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. WWI Theme. Abstract skirmish level combat. Man to Man fighting in the Argonne Forest 1918. One player is the defending American Lost Battalion. The other player is the attacking German Stormtroopers. Victory: You win if you kill both of your opponents Officers.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the combat units. Each player starts with the following assortment of sixteen units: two Officers, ten Riflemen, two Heavy Weapon Specialists, one Runner, and one Sniper.

A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck. Card play determines when units may move and attack. Terrain cards may be used to defeat attack or movement cards.

&ldquo;When two forest fires collide... a ferocious storm unleashes its fury. You must stop the flames at all costs. Do you have what it takes to fight the biggest wildfire of this century? Or are you too busy cowering beneath your computer desk?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Solo card game. Also designed for 2 or more players to compete against each other for best score. Each player is in command of an Army of wildfire fighters & equipment. Protect structures from fire damage to accumulate points.&rdquo;

The game uses two decks of cards. The Battle Card deck is a custom deck consisting of Fighter Cards (different kinds of firefighting crews and equipment), Aid Cards, Challenge Cards, and Leader Cards. The Flame Deck represents the fire and structures or victims using a standard deck of playing cards (including jokers.) The object of the game is to have the most structures once there are no more Flame Cards in the deck or all flames are extinguished.

&ldquo;Card game for 5 players. Based on the 1995 SF PC Game Emperor of the Fading Suns.&rdquo;

In this detailed game of interplanetary struggle and conquest, each player is the leader of a Noble House who is seeking to become the Emperor. Each player starts with control of a Noble House, five random planets, five Scepters, and a War Fleet. Each Noble House has a unique bonus.

The object of the game is to hold the position of Regent for four consecutive turns. The first player to do so is declared Emperor. The Regent is selected by vote of the players, with each Scepter they hold being worth one vote. In addition, a player with the favor of the Church or Guilds may vote with Scepters controlled by those groups. In the case of a tie vote, no player serves as Regent that turn. Scepters can be obtained from other players by making successful attacks.

&ldquo;Card game for 2-4+ players. Theme of Exploration during the 15th to 18th Centuries.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There are 2 Decks: The Expedition Deck. The Exploration Deck.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There are 4 types of cards in the Expedition Deck: Explorer, Ship, Crew, Save. There are 3 types of cards in the Exploration Deck: Ocean, Hazard, Discovery. The Discovery cards themselves when claimed serve as a record of Discovery Points (DP). Discovery cards you claim are kept in your Victory pile.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Victory: The player with the most discovery points at the end of the game is the winner. End of Game: The game ends when the Exploration deck has been gone through twice.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Card, Board, & Dice game for 2-4+ players. Each player is an Eskimo (Inuit) Hunter.&rdquo;

The game is played on a circular track of 16 spaces. There are three types of spaces on the board: shelter, hunting grounds, and ice. Two decks of cards are used, the Animal Deck and the Hunter Deck. The Animal Deck is composed of the animals that may be captured by the players. The Hunter Deck is composed of weapons, means of transportation, and special cards.

&ldquo;Winning: At the end of the game, the player with the most Food Points wins. Food points are gained by collecting (hunting) Animal cards. The game ends when all Animal cards have been collected. Get 1 Food Point for each Special card in your hand at the end of the game.&rdquo;

&ldquo;These solo rules are based on an essentially romantic view of the eskimo and hopefully compliment the multi player Eskimo card and board game by Lloyd Krassner. Why solo??? - No one to play with, thats why.&rdquo;

In addition to splitting the board into the real world and underworld halves, this solitaire variant also adds Fate Cards, Skills and Seasons to the game.

&ldquo;The solo rules are 1 year in the life of your eskimo. One year is 16 steps of the season track.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The upper world (realworld) is bad luck, accident, misadventure and occasionally good luck. To survive you need to manage your resources, your personal strengths, acquire skills and deal with misfortune.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The other world is taboo, transgression, animal guides and recovering your balance in your world.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You need both to survive. You will need to travel in both worlds and maintain balance.&rdquo;

&ldquo;One player takes the role of the Dragon. The other player takes the role of the Slayer (the adventuring party trying to slay the dragon). There are 2 decks: The Dragon Deck. The Slayer Deck.&rdquo;

The Slayer player starts with up to eight randomly selected characters and/or artifacts. The Slayer plays cards to attack the dragon which the Dragon player may attempt to block. The Dragon player then has the opportunity to attack one or more members of the Slayer Party.

&ldquo;Victory: If the Dragon is reduced to 0 or less Hit Points the Slayers win. If all party members are killed, the Dragon wins. The Dragon has 10 hit points. Party Members (Slayers: Heroes & Men-at-Arms) have 1 hit point each. Each unblocked attack by the Dragon will kill one party member. Unblocked attacks by Slayers cause 1 or more hit points of damage to the Dragon.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Takes place 300+ years after the great cataclysm in the world of Krynn. Guide the Companions of the Lance in their exploration of the ruins of Xak Tsaroth to retrieve the Disks of Mishakal needed to defeat Takhisis, the Queen of Darkness. Players share a common deck.&rdquo;

Each turn the player is seeking to capture a foe by playing a foe card along with Hero and Aid cards having a force value higher than the Foe card. The captured Foe card is placed in the player&rsquo;s Victory Pile and the Hero and Aid Cards go in the discard pile.
 &ldquo;Game End: The game ends when there are no cards left in the deck and everyone passes their turn without capturing a Foe card. Victory: The player with the highest Force total in his Victory pile wins the game.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Players take the role of Renegade Time Lords working for the Celestial Intervention Agency. Players must work cooperatively to foil the plots of Temporal Marauders. The goals of Temporal Marauders are the destruction or conquest of Gallifrey, Nexus point Earth, or the Universe.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There are two decks in the game: The Time Lord Deck, and the Temporal Marauder Deck. All players share both decks.&rdquo;

&ldquo;If the players go completely through the Temporal Marauder Deck and defeat all the Marauders, they share a combined win. The player with the most lives + cards in his Victory pile is the first place winner. The next is the second place winner, and so on.&rdquo;

&ldquo;If any Marauder Card ever gets 4 plot tokens on it, the time line is irreversibly disrupted, resulting in universal disaster.  Time and Space unravel. All players lose. Game over.&rdquo;

A science-fiction game of planetary colonization, military conquest, and diplomacy. The game is played on a 5x5 grid. Terrain is randomly generated each game.

&ldquo;Board/Card/Record Keeping game for 2-4+ players. Based on the 1996 Sci-Fi PC Game &lsquo;Deadlock: Planetary Conquest.&rsquo; Races: Each player picks as their identity one of the 7 available races - Human, ChCh-t, Uva Mosk, Tarth, Re&rsquo;Lu, Maug, Cyth. Victory: You win by occupying all territories on the map.&rdquo;

The detailed turn sequence has 20 phases: Upkeep Phase, Labor Phase, Event Phase, Population Phase, Morale Phase, Taxation Phase, Rebellion Phase, Resource Phase, Diplomacy Phase, Trade Phase, Black Market Phase, Build Phase, Production Phase, Ability Phase, Transport Phase, Attack Phase, Plane Return Phase, Colonization Phase, Research Phase, and End Phase.

&ldquo;Medieval Japanese Warfare theme. Each figure represents a company or unit of men. Victory: You win if you kill your opponents Daiyamo.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any other 8x8 grid. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the units, which come in ten types: Daimyo, Ashigaru Spearmen, Bushi Gunners, Bushi Spear Cavalry, Warrior Monks, Samurai Swordsmen, Samurai Horse Archers, Samurai Archers, Samurai Heavy Cavalry and Samurai Naginata. Both players start with an identical assortment of sixteen units which may set up as they desire on their back two rows of the board.

A custom deck of cards is central to the play of the game. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

&ldquo;Simulation of Soviet-American Relations during the Cold War Era (1945-1991). One player takes the role of America (USA). The other player is the Soviets (USSR). Players use Power Tokens to keep track of their Scores in the Areas of Power. Use poker Chips, coins, counters, etc. to represent PT. There are 5 Areas of Power: Military, Economic, Social, Espionage, and Territorial.&rdquo;

&ldquo;There are 3 ways to achieve Victory. General Victory: If your scores in the 5 AOP are greater than your opponent&rsquo;s for two consecutive turns, you win. Power Victory: If your scores in any 3 AOP (except Espionage) are double or greater than your opponent&rsquo;s for two consecutive turns, you win. Crisis Victory: If your opponent goes to zero (or less) in any AOP (except Espionage) you win.&rdquo;

The game provides three setups: Equal, Random, and Historical. Card play generates changes in the AOP levels of the players.

&ldquo;This simple card and dice miniature game is based off of the very original Dungeons and Dragons, back in the days of Chainmail and the Classic Dungeons and Dragons boxed set. If the game rules seem a bit simple and occasionally clumsy, they are supposed to be. That was the charm of the &lsquo;Proto-D&D&rsquo; fantasy miniature wargaming.&rdquo;

&ldquo;This game can be played with 1 to 3 players. For solo play, this is a simple solitaire adventure system for &lsquo;proto-D&D&rsquo; fantasy miniature battles. For two to three players, it becomes a competition to survive (be warned that multiplayer games can get very lengthy; it&rsquo;s best to take this game in sessions like you would a modern D&D adventure, breaking between dungeon levels.)&rdquo;

Each dungeon level uses a different deck of cards composed of the types of monsters found on that level of the dungeon. On each turn the player draws the top card from the deck for the dungeon level his character is on and fights the monster. If the player&rsquo;s character is killed, the player is out of the game. If the monster is defeated, the player receives gold and experience points. A certain number of experience points is required to advance to the lower dungeon levels.

&ldquo;Card game for Aristocratic Adventurers and other Fantasists. Players use melds of cards to retell the tales of the Baron & score points. Victory: The first player to score 100 points wins.&rdquo;

The deck contains seven types of cards, inspired by elements of the Munchausen stories: Dramatic Mood Swings, Extraordinary Companion, Romantic Interlude, Brush with Death, Exotic Location, Preposterous Escape, and Envious Enemy. In addition, there are two Jokers and two Fools.

Unusual twists to the game include the &ldquo;Side Bets and Wagers&rdquo; phase in which players may wager over the truth of &ldquo;any claim whatsoever&rdquo;, with the loser required to give a card (or other agreed upon stake) to the winner of the wager. In addition, there is the &ldquo;Ungentlemanly Conduct Rule&rdquo;, which allows you to steal a random card from an opponent&rsquo;s hand once per game.

&ldquo;A two player game of Fantasy battles using Dice to represent individual units. Object: Play continues until one side routs or is utterly destroyed. Dice: Dice are also referred to as troops and units.&rdquo;

Each type of die represents a different type of Unit in the game. A four-sided die is a General Unit (Leader or Warlord), a six-sided die is an Infantry Unit, an eight-sided die is an Archer Unit, a ten-sided die is a Cavalry Unit, a twelve-sided die is a Mage Unit, and a twenty-sided die is a Monster Unit. The players start with an equal number of dice, but each may choose a different assortment (with each player being limited to one type of monster).

Each turn begins with the players rolling all of their dice. Combat is then resolved by first consulting the Monsters followed, in sequence, by combat separate resolution for Leaders, Mages, Cavalry, Archers, and Infantry.

&ldquo;Millions of years in the future, admits a universe dying a cold, premature death, mankind has overcome great challenges. They have conquered and outlived every alien race. They have overthrown a millennial reign of a cruel quasi-immortal tyrant. They have occupied all the remaining habitable galaxies of the Universe. But their greatest challenge is now themselves. The Human species has evolved into two different peoples: the Morlocks and the Eloi. And now they battle each other to determine which of them shall be masters of the universe.&rdquo;

&ldquo;One player plays the space fleets of the Eloi. The Eloi are a gentle, yet determined people, under the vigilant care of their Empress. They seek to liberate the six galaxies from the cruel Morlocks. One player plays the space fleets of the Morlock Empire. The Morlocks are a fierce and technologically advance people. The only way they wish to serve the Eloi, is on their dinner tables. Each player uses an identical deck of cards. Six sided dice will also be required.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Goal: To win, one player must possess all six of the inhabitable galaxies of the Universe. To capture (or recapture) a galaxy card, one must win a battle by destroying all of the opponent&rsquo;s ships.&rdquo;

&ldquo;The British with superior numbers charge into a shower of cannon shot and sniper fire while attempting to install Ladders over the Rodriguez canal. Their goal is to overrun the American defenders, however their leadership and troop Strength is being decimated. Can the British complete the task before it is too late? Victory: The Americans win if all British units are destroyed. The British win if all American units are overrun. Otherwise the British score is the number of American units that were overrun. The British player with the highest score wins.&rdquo;

In this abstract wargame, set during the War of 1812, the British units are represented by six-sided dice. The face-up number shows the strength of each unit. The units are moved down a twenty space track. Moving dice off the end of the track helps reduce the strength of the American forces by removing cards from the American Troop deck. The British win when all American Troop cards have been eliminated.

The game may be played in three different ways: solitaire, two-player (American versus British), or multiplayer (two or more players play the British competing for high score).

&ldquo;Space empires against each other and the bug threat.&rdquo;

The map is randomly constructed, drawn on a piece of paper. Each player selects a starting world for his empire. A random number of worlds (1-6) are infected by Bug units, which reproduce and spread to other worlds. The players each start with one frigate, one freighter, ten troops, six food units, and six machinery units. Agricultural worlds provide one food unit per turn. Industrial worlds convert one food unit to one machinery unit each turn.

The winner is the player who has the most victory points after ten turns. Victory points are awarded at the end of each turn based on the types of worlds controlled, for each cruiser owned, and for having the longest trade route.

Inspired by Fred Saberhagen's Berserker series.

&ldquo;Human fleet vs a Berserker Ship. Abstract skirmish level Ship combat. Each figure represents a single Ship (unit).  Victory: Destroy the opposing fleet.&rdquo;

The game is played on an 8x8 grid or chessboard. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the ships. The Human Fleet player has a force of sixteen ships against the single Berserker ship. Each ship is rated for hit points, speed, and attack range. The players draw a hand of cards from a common deck and card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

A card game based on the fantasy creations of artist H.R. Giger.

&ldquo;Players raise armies of Biomechanoids to destroy each other with. Victory: Reduce your opponent to zero hits. Each player starts with 20 hits.&rdquo;

The game is played using a deck of over 120 cards, which come in seven types: Location, Biomechanoid, Feature, Artifact, Action, Reaction, and Destiny.

&ldquo;Solo Card game based on the Blade Movies/Comics. Blade is a Daywalker Vampire Slayer.&rdquo;

The game is played with two decks, the Aid Deck and the Foe Deck. The latter contains various Foes and Locations. Blade starts with twenty Blood Points and five Aid Cards. He must battle a series of Foes at a number of different locations.

&ldquo;Victory: You win if at the beginning of Foe Phase all Foe cards in the game are in the Foe discard pile. You lose if Blade is reduced to zero or less Blood Points.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Board & card game for 2 players. Oriental Martial Arts Theme. Abstract skirmish level combat. Man to Man fighting. Victory: You win if you kill your opponents Leader.&rdquo;

The game is played on an 8x8 grid or chessboard. Miniatures or counters are used to represent the men, which come in three types: Leaders, Bodyguards, and Followers. The players also choose they type of Warrior Band they are playing: Samurai, Ninja, Monk or Bushi.

Each type of Warrior Band uses a custom deck of cards which is central to the play of the game. Card play determines when units may move, attack, and defend.

&ldquo;Napoleonic era tactical combat simulation. Watch out for grapeshot.&rdquo;

Each player is given 100 points to construct a force from the following types of units: Infantry (1 point), Cavalry (1.5 points), Cannon (10 points), Officer (3 points), and Baggage (supply wagons, 2 points). Each player also receives a Flag unit &ldquo;for games of capture the Flag.&rdquo; The players must also construct their own map of the battlefieldt using four abstracted terrain types: Clear, Covered, Fortified, and Impassable.

The object of the game is to obtain the most Victory Points, which are awarded in varying amounts for killing or capturing units.

&ldquo;Simulates a car chase between the Law and a Fugitive. Winning: The Fugitive wins if the Law does not catch him at the end of 7 turns.&rdquo;

The game uses a custom deck with seven types of cards: Investigation, Fugitive, Chase, Escape, Capture, and Location. At the start of each turn the players fill their hands up to ten cards, with the option to discard and redraw up to five. The remainder of the turn consists of up to three phases of card play - the Search Phase, Chase Phase, and Escape Phase.

The turn ends with any Phase that the Law player loses. The Law player must win a series of all three Phases to capture the Fugitive and win the game.

&ldquo;Players control Arabian caravans going back and forth across the deserts, acting as Middlemen between Europe and the Orient.&rdquo;

The game is played on a chessboard or any similar 8x8 grid. Row 1 on the board represents Europe, row 8 is the Orient, and rows 2 through 7 are designated Middle Eastern rows. Each Middle Eastern row receives one Oasis and one Quicksand marker on different random spaces. Four pawns are used &ndash; one for each player to represent their caravans, one to represent Bandits, and one to represent a Sandstorm. An eight-sided die is required for play.

A Players chooses to start in Europe or the Orient. Players draw cards to obtain goods or soldiers, and to collect movement cards. Players then play movement cards to transport their goods to the opposite end of the board where they may be sold for Gold. The first player to accumulate fifty Gold is the winner.

&ldquo;Card game using concepts from general biology. The deck includes 85 cards. Object: Accumulate the most points at the end of the game, or over several games.&rdquo;

Each player is dealt a hand of eight cards from which they attempt to play special combinations. Over forty combinations are defined, such as Photosynthesis (using the cards Chloroplast, Chlorophyll, Light Reactions, Dark Reactions), Sexual Reproduction (using Gametes, Fertilization, Zygote), and Mitosis (with Mitosis, Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase.)

One point is scored for each card in the combination. The game ends once there are no cards left in the deck or any time a player has no cards left in his hand.

&ldquo;Players take the role of Celtic Warrior Heroes in ancient Ireland. Players compete to make their Hero the most famous of all. The winner will be sung about by bards for generations and his exploits will be written of in the Book of Kells.&rdquo;

The game comes in two versions, Ulster and Fionn. A separate deck of custom cards is used for each version.

The players accumulate cards to score points in four categories: Blessings, Fortune, Victory, and Prophecy. The player who has accumulated the most points in the most categories after seven turns wins the game.

&ldquo;Chinese symbolism theme with rummy/poker mechanics. The Deck: Players share a common deck. The deck contains 27 cards. There are 5 Suites each with 5 cards numbered 1-5.&rdquo;

The five suits are Elements, Blessings, Virtues, Directions, and Beasts for Sacrifice. In addition there is one Ying and one Yang card. The first player to play a five card meld wins the games.

There are three types of melds: flush, straight (all from different suits), and five of a  kind. The Yin card serves as a wild card for a flush, the Yang cards serves as a wild card for a five of a kind.

&ldquo;Historical period: Florida 1513 (Ponce de Leon) &ndash; 1821 (American posession). Each player represents one colonial power: Spanish, British, or French. The Deck: Players share the Enhancement deck. The deck contains two types of cards: Income Cards & Combatants.&rdquo;

These cards are played onto an abstract map of Florida, a ring of 36 spaces marked with the names of geographic features and locations of settlements. The players gain income by controlling settlements.

The first player to accumulate 50 Gold is the winner.

&ldquo;Canaan circa 1300 &ndash; 1100 BC. Each player represents one Nation vying for control of Canaan (Palestine.) The land of Canaan is represented by a pool of 20 City Tokens. Tokens (of a different color) are also used to keep track of Armies. Each Army Token a player owns generates 1 Force in the Conquest Phase. Each Army Token roughly represents 1,000 men. Victory: At the end of 20 turns, the player with the most City Tokens wins.&rdquo;

Each player plays one of seven nations of the ancient Middle East. Each nation has a special ability. Through card play the players fight battles to gain control of Canaan.

This is a free game which requires paper, pencil, and your own created cards, maps, tokens, and dice.  Directions for play are on the Warp Spawn Games website.  Create your own game and place the images with the link below!

Custer's Last Stand is a Tactical level Free mini-wargame. 
American West: Indians vs Soldiers. Each figure represents a group of cavalry soldiers or Indian braves. Victory: Destroy your enemies completely.&rdquo;

The game is played on an 8x8 grid or chessboard. The middle four squares are each occupied by one Soldier. All edge spaces each contain one Indian. A custom deck of cards is key to the game play. The players draw hands of cards from the shared deck. Card play determines when units may move, attack, or defend.

&ldquo;Mad Max style post-apocalyptic gang-warfare road combat.&rdquo;

Each player starts with a random assortment of six vehicles, each of which has a random piece of equipment (mostly weaponry of some sort) which can be used a random number of times as determined by the roll of a six-sided die. The road is a track 100 spaces long with randomly distributed obstacles.

One player is designated as the Slow Gang, the other player is designated as the Fast Gang. The Slow Gang vehicles start at one end of the track and must try to reach the other end. The Fast Gang player may place his vehicles on any space on the track. The Slow Gang player wins by getting at least three vehicles to the opposite end of the track, otherwise the Fast Gang player wins.

&ldquo;Short rules for a quick play civilization like boardgame.&rdquo;

Two or more players begin the game with one city and ten counters representing the population and military force. A standard deck of cards is used. A certain type of card, or combination of cards, must be played to perform certain actions in the game. The descriptions of the combinations include: Migration, Merchant, Combat, Apostle, Abundance, Exploration, War, Exodus, Colonization, Crusade, and Foundation.

The object of the game is to control more than half of the provinces on the map. A player who is eliminated may return as a foreign invader, starting with one city and six counters on the outer ring of provinces.

&ldquo;Solo Card Game. 10 May 1940. The player takes the role of the Germans invading the Western Democracies. There are two decks: The Allied Deck and the German Deck.&rdquo;

To advance your campaign, you must play melds with a higher Force total than the Allied Cards on the table.

&ldquo;Objective: You win if you run the Allied deck out of cards. The Allied forces collapse and you conquer France in 6 weeks. If you ever accumulate 7 delay tokens, the Allies have stopped you and you must fight a long war against France.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You control a US Marine Company on Patrol in Fallujah.&rdquo;

The game uses a custom deck of sixty cards. There are ten different kinds of cards in the deck: Insurgent Tactics, Insurgents, Positions, Explosives, American Tactics, Infantry, Armor, Support , Recon, and Disarm.

The player&rsquo;s score is based on how many casualties are suffered by the player's Company versus the number inflicted on the enemy.

&ldquo;Combat between 2 opposing fantasy warbands. Game progresses in 2 stages: Recruit Stage. Battle Stage.&rdquo;

In the Recruit Stage, the players create their warbands by receiving a random selection of ten warriors to which they must assign their random assortments of weapons and armor cards.

The game is played with five decks of cards -- the Warrior, Weapon, Armor, Spell and Fight Decks.

The king of the Goblins left. He left behind him only these words: &ldquo;My friends, I need a holiday. I separated and hid my treasure in the four corners of the Large Forest. He who would find the greatest part of it will become king in my place.&rdquo;

Each player directs a tribe of Goblins. During the rush towards the places where the treasures are hidden, players  will have to use their Goblins, in order to find the greatest number of parts of the treasure.

When the 5 parts of the treasure are found, the player which finds the greatest number of it is declared King of the Goblins.

&ldquo;You are a brave pilot battling against enemy ships from another world. You must use your skill and cunning to survive not only the threat from enemy forces but also the evil alien race known as the Bogons.&rdquo;

2 to 6 Players can play this simple, and fun, card game. Have you got what it takes to become a Galactic Hero?

The files needed to make this Print and Play Card Game can be purchased from http://www.wargamedownloads.com/item.php?item=662&pics
